. Sollors suggests that although the transformation of this settler country into a polyethnic and self-consciously multicultural nation may appear as a story of great progress toward the fulfillment of egalitarian ideals, deepening economic inequality actually exacerbates the divisions among Americans today.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aCriticismxAmericanxAfrican American.-bisacsh. 0aCriticismxAmericanxGeneral.-bisacsh. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aHistoryxGeneral.-bisacshzUnited States. 0aImmigrants in literature. 0aMulticulturalism in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aSocial sciencesxDiscrimination and Race Relations.-bisacsh. 0aSocial sciencesxEthnic StudiesxAfrican American Studies.-bisacsh. 0aSocial sciencesxEthnic StudiesxGeneral.-bisacsh. 4aamerican culture. 4aanglo-american. 4adiversity. 4aegalitarian. 4aellis island. 4ajamestown. 4amulticultural. 4apilgrims. 4apolyethnic. 4aunity. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813589350zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813589350423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813589350.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  RUP eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK